	<div id="id17e6" class="post">
		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="45" alt="Don’t panic, it’s boutique" width="318" class="title" src="../../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/d2173f7f"/><span class="title">Don’t panic, it’s boutique</span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">Doctor Barnett</span>, <span>on March 9, 2006</span></span>
			<span id="id17e7" class="tags">
					{&nbsp;<span><a href="../../../city/tag/organic/#selected-tag"><span>organic</span></a><span id="id17e8">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../city/tag/marketing/#selected-tag"><span>marketing</span></a><span id="id17e9">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../city/tag/food/#selected-tag"><span>food</span></a><span id="id17ea">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../city/tag/shopping/#selected-tag"><span>shopping</span></a></span>&nbsp;}
			</span>
		</span></div>
		<div><p>From a comment on <a href="http://technically.us/eat/articles/2006/03/07/trader-joes-a-rant">Eat</a> :</p>


	<blockquote>
		<p>They [Trader Joe&#8217;s] also sell great breakfast cereal. So great that we go out to the burbs to get it because it is the only cereal we will eat.</p>
	</blockquote>


	<p>Dear buyers of so-called organic products,</p>


	<p><strong>You&#8217;re getting conned.</strong> Not just about the contents of those products (because <em>organic</em>, as popularly used, means nothing) but about the choice that&#8217;s happening in your own head.</p>


	<p>Organic products are marketed as healthier for you and better for the earth than what are contemptuously called conventional products. And some of them probably are. But the reason these products have been steamrolling over traditional brands (or, just, plain ol&#8217; head of lettuce) is far more powerful than health and the environment: it&#8217;s a shift in our consumer culture from mass market to boutique branding.</p>


	<p><img src="/pictures/brand-wheel.jpg" alt="" /></p>


	<p>Consider a product that has seen similar disprution but that most vendors aren&#8217;t quite cynical enough to label organic: <strong>beer</strong>. From the dawn of time until ten years ago, everyone both rich and poor was content to drink from the same vat of Budweiser, Miller, and Coors. But how do these brands sound in 2006? Old, cheap, and and in bad taste. &#8220;I&#8217;ll take a Heinek— no, make that a <em>Stella Artois</em>.&#8221;</p>


	<p>The brands haven&#8217;t changed, but the buyers sure have. From Brooklyn to the O.C., people are choosing Starbucks over Folgers, Beck&#8217;s over Budweiser, and Kashi over Cheerios. It&#8217;s not the taste of a new generation, either. Just look at your parents: they&#8217;ve <a href="http://www.slate.com/id/2089129/">traded up</a> as well.</p>


	<p>Is Kashi any better for you, or even more &#8220;natural&#8221; than Cheerios? No one knows, and no one really even cares. All that matters is that &#8220;Kashi Orginic Promise&#8221; looks and tastes different, and costs comfortably more. Of course the shine will wear off, even more quickly with a brand name as cheesy as theirs, and that&#8217;s my point: there is no organic revolution, just an organic trend.</p>


	<p>What&#8217;s really happening is that food is catching up with the trendiness of the rest of our culture. &#8220;Organic,&#8221; when it starts to sound too ’90s, will vanish in a puff of oatmeal. (Just watch.) Food brands will come and go more quickly, and people will make foolish herd shopping decisions even more hastily than before. It&#8217;s not the end of the world, though all that nutritional shuffling might not be so good for your insides.</p>


	<p>Of course as most people reading this know, my paycheck comes entirely from the fickle trendiness of cityfolk. Our business depends on people buying into overpriced fashions in the twinkling of an eye. Sometimes, we do run pieces about organic hoo-ha. (That has lately slowed to a trickle.)</p>


	<p>The reason <em>I</em> don&#8217;t feel bad is we play it straight. We <strong>are</strong> a styles and trends publication. We joke about the twists and turns of fashion. And most importantly, the majority of our readers (those smart enough to know advertisements from editorial) are in on the the game.</p>


	<p>They don&#8217;t think, for example, that they had a personal enological revelation in 2003 that Merlot just sucks. They know that Merlot <em>went out of style</em> because we started taking cheap shots at it, that&#8217;s all. Are organic shoppers in on the game? Chumps buying <a href="http://shop.store.yahoo.com/freywine/orme20.html">this doosey</a> sure aren&#8217;t.</p>


	<p>So, <strong>Trader Joe&#8217;s, eat your prepackaged heart out.</strong> Help people spend time in the kitchen without <a href="http://technically.us/eat/articles/2006/03/07/trader-joes-a-rant">cooking the chicken</a> if that&#8217;s your absurd mission. There&#8217;s nothing I can do about it but gripe, which I certainly will do.</p>


	<p>And when your fortunes start to wane, Trader Man, remember those advertisements I mentioned. We&#8217;ll help you unload your cat-shaped cookies, but we won&#8217;t do it for cheap.</p></div>
